<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: LATINO LEADERS CALL FOR OUSTER OF 
SUPERVISORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Citing a federal finding that Los Angeles County's Health Services Department 
discriminated against Latinos, community leaders Tuesday said on-the-job bias 
will continue until the supervisors are voted out of office. 
</P>
<P>
"About the only thing we can continue to do is to work to vote them (the 
supervisors) out," said Raul Nunez of the Los Angeles County Chicano Employees 
Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Last week, the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission accused the county 
of job discrimination, singling out County-USC and Martin Luther King Jr./Drew 
medical centers for failing to hire and promote Latinos. County officials have 
said under-representation of Latinos in the county work force is the result of 
slowed hirings due to budget cuts. 
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the supervisors called for a county study of Health Services 
Department hiring practices. 
