<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: CAMARILLO; 
</P>
<P>
ART SHOW RIBBONS GIVE PATIENTS A BOOST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TINA DAUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ribbons have been awarded and now the fun begins, said Jack Cheney, the art 
therapist at Camarillo State Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
For the past week, patients at Camarillo have been stopping in Cheney's little 
studio tucked in a corner of the hospital to pick up their works of art, a 
small cash prize and ribbons from the Ventura County Fair. 
</P>
<P>
According to Cheney, nearly 140 paintings, sketchings and pastels created by 
mentally ill and developmentally disabled patients at the hospital received 
awards. 
</P>
<P>
About 240 works were entered in the annual competition. Forty-one received blue 
ribbons. 
</P>
<P>
He said he encourages patients to enter their works in the fair because the 
recognition gives them a boost. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a real good showcase for their art," he said. TINA DAUNT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Patty Peterson, left, and Cherie Goss show their award-winning 
paintings. JAMES REUBSAMEN / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
