</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANCHORAGE, Alaska 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dozens of Prudhoe Bay oil-field workers were evacuated after a fire broke out 
in a warehouse and threatened to engulf a nitrogen-processing plant, 
authorities said today. 
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation said they were 
worried that the fire could cause chemicals to spill on the tundra, the 
delicate Arctic layer of plants that can take years to regenerate. 
</P>
<P>
Occupancy of the Prudhoe Bay Hotel, about 4 miles from the fire, swelled to 
about 500 people, up from the usual 260, acting manager Staci Bolley said 
today. 
